gland":"England","Westhampnett, Sussex, England":"Westhampnett, Sussex, England, United Kingdom","Northamptonshire, England":"Northamptonshire, England","East Grinstead, Sussex, England":"East Grinstead, Sussex, England","West Hoathley, Sussex, England.":"West Hoathley, Sussex, England, United Kingdom","Kerry, Montgomeryshire, Wales":"Kerry, Montgomeryshire, Wales","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705181,"age":13,"year":"1035","julianDay":2099086,"title":"England Divided","description":"King Canute died in 1035 and England was divided between his three sons. His son Sweyn received Norway, Harthacanute received Denmark, and Harold Harefoot received North England.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705182,"age":44,"year":"1066","julianDay":2110409,"title":"Battle of Hastings","description":"Battle of Hastings was fought between the Norman-French army and the battle-wary English army on October 14, 1066. Duke William of Normandy believed he was the rightful king rather than Harold, who had been crowned king several months earlier. Harold was killed in battle and William was crowned king on Christmas Day 1066.","url":"https://www.english-heritage.org.uk/learn/1066-and-the-norman-conquest/what-happened-battle-hastings/","urlTitle":"English Heritage - Battle of Hastings","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When William de Waterville was born in 1022, in Westhampnett, Sussex, England, his father, Robert de Waterville I, was 23 and his mother, Faelis verch Llewlen, was 19. He married Faelia verch Llewton in 1068, in West Hoathley, Sussex, England, United Kingdom. He died in 1085, in Westhampnett, Sussex, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 63."},"et":{"1022–1085":"1022–1085","1030–Female":"1030–Surnud","1027–Female":"1027–Surnud","1048–1085":"1048–1085","1052–Male":"1052–Surnud","1080–1162":"1080–1162","1000–1085":"1000–1085","1004–Female":"1004–Surnud","1080":"1080","about 1052":"umbes 1052","about 1085":"umbes 1085","about 1080":"umbes 1080","1022":"1022","1066":"1066","1000":"1000","1085":"1085","1162":"1162","1052":"1052","1030":"1030","1027":"1027","1048":"1048","1004":"1004","1068":"1068","1035":"1035","Rudham, Norfolk, England":"Norfolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"England","Westhampnett, Sussex, England":"Westhampnett, Sussex, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Northamptonshire, England":"Northamptonshire, England","East Grinstead, Sussex, England":"East Grinstead, Sussex, England","West Hoathley, Sussex, England.":"West Hoathley, Sussex, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Kerry, Mont